President Barack Obama has proclaimed April 9, 2013, as National Former Prisoner of War Recognition Day. In his proclamation, he pays tribute to the former prisoners of war who sacrificed their freedom for the defense of the country. He acknowledges the trials and hardships these service members endured, with many losing their lives. Despite their circumstances, they showed immense courage and strength. The President emphasizes the importance of honoring their service every day, not just on this designated day. He calls for a full accounting of those still missing and highlights the need to provide support and stability for the veterans who have returned home. The proclamation encourages all Americans to observe this day by honoring all American prisoners of war, service members, and veterans. The President also urges government officials and organizations to hold appropriate ceremonies and activities to commemorate this day.